<br>
        My body aches from training.  'Tis only my first week, and my body has yet to adjust to the rigors of it.  I long for home, and my soft bed. . . and the smell of mother's cooking, and my father's strong arms.  I  miss them terribly.  I hope I am able to see them soon.<br>
<br>
        I nearly jump from my seat, as the barmaid's voice startles me. &quot;What can I get for you lil lady?&quot; she asked.  Her inquisitive eyes probing my face, as she smiles a knowing smile.  I felt anger rise within me. &quot;How dare she call me 'lil',&quot; but my mind and body were too tired to respond at this point.  Besides, I am sure she meant no ill by it. &quot;A bowl of stew, bread and a hardy ale please,&quot; I reply in a voice gruff with fatigue.  She flashes a smile and winks as she replies, &quot;Coming right up! I'll bring you something special that I'm sure will meet your Dwarven tastes.&quot;  With that, the barmaid whisks off.  <br>
<br>
I lean back once again, thinking of home.  I stroke my beard, remembering that of my father.  I smile as I think of my father, a respected warrior and revered smith among the Dwarven people, and my mother, a gentile healer of the Underfoot and a baker of some fame.  Here I am,  their daughter and only child.  I had desired to follow in the footsteps of one of my parents.  Alas, I had neither the strength required for the warrior guild, nor the proficiency with magic the clerics sought.  I, however, did have some talent with the magics, which my mother helped me hone as a child.  My father also taught me young how to use sword and shield.  Father was always adamant about me being able to defend myself, even against the school children who would pick fights with me simply because I had a beard.  I've often wondered why I was blessed with beard as Mother did not have one.  It was a source of ridicule among the children at times, but I never really let it get to me.   I think the ridicule bothered my father more than it did me.   I suppose that was part of the strength I inherited from my father, more of an emotional strength than a physical one.  Add to that a heart of compassion from my mother.  I guess it was no surprise that I wound up at the paladin guild.        <br>
<br>
        &quot;Here ya go m'lady,&quot; the barmaid said as she sets down a steaming bowl of stew, loaf of bread and a glass of dark ale. Startled again, but too tired to respond, I simlpy look up.   &quot;If ya need anythin' more, just holler for Drixa,&quot; she proclaimed with a smile and a wink.  I nod appreciatively, too worn out to speak.  I slowly eat the stew, the broth feeling good on my parched throat.  I finish my meal, and I nestle back preparing to enjoy my ale.  Its color is so dark. . . I'm not sure 've seen such before.  I bring the mug to my lips, drinking deep.  I smile as I swallow.  The barmaid had not lied, 'twas indeed an ale fitting of my tastes.  The perfect end to a rough day.<br>
<br>
Keku<br>
